# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- OpenZeppelin proxy stack: `ERC1967Upgrade`, `ERC1967Proxy`, `TransparentUpgradeableProxy`, `BeaconProxy`, `UpgradeableBeacon`, `Proxy`, `ProxyAdmin` — recurring focus on upgrade execution, initialization, admin routing, and beacon control
- Supporting utilities/interfaces: `Address`, `StorageSlot`, `Ownable`, `IERC1967`, `IERC1822`, `IBeacon`, `Context` — mainly relevant for delegatecall behavior, slot correctness, and ownership/admin invariants around proxy flows
- Deployment/setup paths: payable proxy constructors with optional initializer payloads — repeatedly relevant to skipped setup delegatecalls and possible stranded ETH at deployment

## Issue Directions Seen
- Upgrade and initialization sequencing across ERC-1967 / transparent / beacon flows remains the main audit direction, especially where delegatecall-based setup or migration changes authority or state assumptions
- Transparent proxy admin/non-admin dispatch is a durable hotspot: non-admin calls delegate into the implementation, so implementation-defined upgrade logic can remain reachable through the proxy despite transparent admin gating
- Admin-control and storage-slot invariants are a recurring review axis, including `ProxyAdmin` / beacon ownership and shared reliance on the ERC-1967 implementation slot
- Beacon upgrade behavior remains a watched but unconfirmed direction, including initialization flow and risks tied to implementation resolution during proxy execution
- Payable deployment behavior remains a concrete concern: constructor ETH can be accepted while empty initializer data skips setup execution, leaving funds stranded if no later recovery path exists
- Governance-side ownership transitions such as `renounceOwnership()` on upgrade-control contracts remain relevant background context even when not retained as findings

## Useful Context
- Audit attention is still concentrated on upstream OpenZeppelin upgradeability infrastructure rather than protocol-specific business logic
- Highest scrutiny stays on proxy entrypoints and upgrade plumbing; helper libraries are mostly supporting context for slot and call semantics
- Transparent and beacon proxies are treated as distinct trust surfaces, but both are analyzed through the same core lenses: delegatecall reachability, upgrade authority, and initialization ordering
- Documented hazards such as selector clashes, delegatecall edge cases, and stateful-beacon/TOCTOU-style concerns have been examined as review directions, but not all have produced retained findings
- No cross-agent divergence is visible so far; the memory reflects a single, consistent review thread centered on upgradeability mechanics and deployment-time fund handling
